The American National Election Studies surveys a representative sample of US voters prior to and following each US Presidential Election. We will use their survey from the last US Presidential Election (held in 2020) to learn more about US voters.

Tip

The nes data set in the polsciols R package provides you with a selection of the hundreds of questions the ANES asked of all 8,280 respondents to the 2020 survey. Each row provides data for one respondent.

Part B

Points: 3

Note

3/3

In large populations, IQ test scores are standardized to have a mean of 100 and a standard deviation of 15. In what way does the distribution among these students differ from the overall population? Do not use the words and phrases âmeanâ or âstandard deviationâ in your answer.

mean <- mean(iq)
sd <- sd(iq)
standard <- (iq-mean)/sd * 15 + 100
barplot(iq, main = "IQ Scores", xlab = "Student Scores", ylab= "mean")

When compared to the overall population, the students had a higher distribution of IQ values. This suggests that the tested group of kids generally had higher IQ test scores. Compared to a larger population, the variation in scores are a little bit smaller, indicating that the scores in this group are more closely distributed around their central values.

Question 5

The ANES also asked respondents prior to the election to rate Joe Biden and Donald Trump on a scale from 0 to 100.

Part A

Points: 3

Note

3/3

Plot all respondentsâ answers to these two questions on a single density plot. There are several peaks in these distributions. What do these peaks have in common? What might they suggest about how people answer questions that ask them to provide a single number along a large range?

ggplot(nes) +
 geom_density(aes(x=therm_biden), fill = "blue", alpha = 0.4) +
 geom_density(aes(x=therm_trump), fill = "red", alpha = 0.4)+
 labs(
    x= "Feelings about Biden & Trump", 
   y= "Density"
 )

The peaks in the data suggest that more people have negative feelings towards both Biden & Trump. There are some tiny peaks around the 50âs, for that I would assume respondents rounded up. I would argue that, that those responses could be seen as indifferent to both. All of the peaks are the same for both Biden & Trump, I believe that suggest that there is an equal dislike for both. This suggests that when asked on a scale from 0-100 respondents are more likely to chose 1, 50, or 100.

Part B

Points: 3

Note

2/3

President Biden won this election. Would you predict this outcome from the way this representative sample responded to these questions? Provide a brief description of the reasoning behind your answer.

I would predict that Biden would win. I would predict this because while there is a peak for both at zero rating, the peak for Trump is higher than Bidenâs.
